import java.util.HashMap;

public static boolean valid_partition(int[] nums) {
    HashMap<Integer, Integer> count = new HashMap<>();
    for (int num : nums) {
        count.put(num, count.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
    }
    for (int num : count.keySet()) {
        int cnt = count.get(num);
        if (cnt == 2 || cnt == 3 || (count.containsKey(num - 1) && count.containsKey(num + 1))) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```

    The function first counts the frequency of each element in the given array. After that, it iterates through the counted elements map, checking whether there's a valid partition by checking the conditions: the count of the element must be exactly 2 or 3, or the element should be in the middle of a consecutive sequence (i.e., the current element minus 1 and the current element plus 1 should be present in the counted elements map as well). If at least one valid partition is found, the function returns true, otherwise false.
